I did some reading on Dependency Injection, and I think I got the hang of it. But I feel like I explain it better when I use examples. So here's one:
Let's say we have some code that needs a database to work. It looks something like this:

public interface IDbFactory
{
    IQueryable GetData();
}

public interface IQueryable
{
    IEnumerable<MyObject> Get();
}

public class MyObject
{
    public string Property1 { get; set; }
    public string Property2 { get; set; }
}

public class DataAccessLayer
{
    private readonly IDbFactory _dbFactory;

    public DataAccessLayer(IDbFactory dbFactory)
    {
        _dbFactory = dbFactory;
    }

    public IEnumerable<MyObject> Get()
    {
        //implemented in a concrete class
    }
}

Now, if you want to use dependency injection, you would create an instance of both the Factory and Queryable interfaces, and pass them into the DataAccessLayer. Here's what that would look like:

public class DependencyInjectionExample
{
    public DependencyInjectionExample()
    {
        var dbFactory = new MockDbFactory();
        var queryable = new MockQueryable();

        var dataAccessLayer = new DataAccessLayer(dbFactory, queryable);
    }
}

public interface MockDbFactory
{
    IQueryable GetData();
}
public interface MockQueryable
{
    IEnumerable<MyObject> Get();
}

public class MockDbFactory : IDbFactory
{
    public IQueryable GetData()
    {
        return null;
    }
}

